{"cursor":"73281","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox military person |honorific_prefix = Field Marshal The Right\nHonourable |name = The Viscount Montgomery of Alamein |honorific_suffix\n= KG GCB DSO PC |birth_date = |death_date = |birth_place =\nKennington, London |death_place = Alton, Hampshire |placeofburial = Holy Cross\nChurchyard, Binsted |placeofburial_label= Place of burial |image = \n|caption = Montgomery wearing his beret with two cap badges. |nicknames = Monty,\nThe Spartan General |allegiance = |branch = British Army |serviceyears =\n1908â1958 |rank = Field Marshal |commands = Eighth Army 1942â1943 Allied\n21st Army Group 1943â1945 Chief of the Imperial General Staff\n1946â1948 Deputy Supreme Commander Europe of NATO 1951â1958 |battles = First\nWorld War Anglo-Irish War Arab revolt in Palestine Second World War\n|awards = KG (1946) GCB (1945) DSO (1914) MID (9 times) Other\nforeign awards (listed in main text) |laterwork =Colonel Commandant, Royal Tank\nRegiment Colonel Commandant, Parachute Regiment ( -\n1956 )Representative Colonel Commandant, Royal Armoured Corps (1947 -\n1957 )Colonel Commandant, Army Physical Training Corps (1946 -\n1960 )Colonel Royal Warwickshire Regiment(1947 -\n1963 )Deputy Lieutenant of Southampton (1958â) }}\n\nField Marshal 'Bernard Law Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein', KG,\nGCB, DSO, PC (; 17 November 1887 â 24 March 1976), nicknamed '\"Monty\"' and\nthe '\"Spartan General\"', was a British Army officer.\n\nHe saw action in the First World War, where he was seriously wounded, and during\nthe Second World War he commanded the Eighth Army from August 1942 in the\nWestern Desert until the final Allied victory in Tunisia. This command included\nthe Battle of El Alamein, a turning point in the Western Desert Campaign. He\nsubsequently commanded the Eighth Army in Sicily and Italy before being given\nresponsibility for planning the D-Day invasion in Normandy. He was in command of\nall Allied ground forces during Operation Overlord from the initial landings\nuntil after the Battle of Normandy. He then continued in command of the 21st\nArmy Group for the rest of the campaign in North West Europe. As such he was the\nprincipal field commander for the failed airborne attempt to bridge the Rhine at\nArnhem and the Allied Rhine crossing. On 4 May 1945 he took the German surrender\nat Luneburg Heath in northern Germany. After the war he became Commander-in-\nChief of the British Army of the Rhine (BAOR) in Germany and then Chief of the\nImperial General Staff.\n","linknr":1379,"url":"Bernard_Montgomery","recorded":1362538068,"links":109,"instances":["world_war_ii","cryptography","administrator","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","canadian_army_officer","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","london","united_kingdom","london","1917","military","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","bishop","belgium","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","army","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","1942","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","france","cocktail","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","west_riding_infantry_division","british_army_and_royal_marines","united_kingdom","united_kingdom","2nd_london_division"],"pdf":["http://www.societies.cam.ac.uk/cuhags/escutcheon/09.3.pdf"],"categories":["1887 births","1976 deaths","British Field Marshals","British World War II Field Marshals","British Army personnel of World War I","British military personnel of the Irish War of Independence","Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath","Knights of the Garter","Companions of the Distinguished Service Order","Foreign recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (United States)","Chief Commanders of the Legion of Merit","Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst","Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914–1918 (France)","Recipients of the Croix de Guerre (Belgium)","Knights of the Elephant","Grand Commanders of the Order of George I","Recipients of t